Distributed systems divide files into chunks and
replicate those chunks across multiple storage nodes.
This ensures redundancy, availability, and fault
tolerance. If one node becomes unavailable, the
system can retrieve chunks from another replica node.

Chunking improves scalability because large files are
broken into smaller manageable units. Replication
ensures reliability and recovery in case of node
failure.

AES-256 encryption protects data confidentiality.
SHA-256 hashing verifies chunk integrity before
merging the original file again.

This project demonstrates:
- File chunking
- Chunk distribution
- Replication
- Fault tolerance
- File merging
- Distributed storage
- Metadata management
- Encryption
- Integrity verification

